Q1.Why is a NumPy array faster than a Python list internally?
NumPy arrays are faster because they store data in contiguous memory and are implemented in C.

Q2.What is vectorization? Why is it preferred over loops?
Vectorization means performing operations on whole arrays without loops. It is faster than Python loops.

Q3.Explain contiguous memory allocation and how it improves performance.
Contiguous memory means data is stored continuously in memory, improving cache efficiency and speed.

Q4.What happens internally when you execute:
b = a
instead of
b = a.copy()
b = a creates a reference to the same array.
b = a.copy() creates an copy.

Q5.Differentiate between:
reshape() : Changes shape
flatten() : Returns copy in 1D
ravel() : Returns view in 1D

Q6.What is broadcasting?
Give one practical example
Broadcasting allows NumPy to perform operations on arrays of different shapes.
a = np.array([1,2,3])
a + 5
o/p : [6 7 8]

Q7.When will broadcasting fail?Explain with an example.
Broadcasting fails when shapes are incompatible.
a = np.array([1,2,3])
b = np.array([1,2])
a+b

Q8.What is the difference between:
a * b
and
np.matmul(a,b)
a * b is element wise multipication and np.matmul(a,b) is matrix mult

Q9.Why does NumPy force arrays to have a fixed datatype?
Fixed datatype allows efficient memory usage and faster computations.

Q10.Explain the purpose of:
axis=0
axis=1
